<h3>Annotating Patterns</h3>
<p>Pattern annotation gives designers and developers the ability to provide context for their patterns. It should follow the Front Matter (YAML + Markdown) format:</p>
<pre><code>  ---
  el: #title
  title: Title for my pattern
  ---
  This is a *Markdown* description of my pattern.
</code></pre>
<p>
<code>el</code> must be a CSS selector identifying the element to annotate. A tooltip will appear above the element, and the annotation's title and description will be rendered in the Annotation Viewer.
</p>
<p>
An annotation file normally has a <code>.md</code> file extension, although this can be configured in <code>patternlab-config.json</code> under <code>frontMatterExtension</code>. The rest of the name must match the name of the pattern it's documenting. For example, to document the following pattern:
</p>
<pre><code>  00-elements/images/landscape-16x9.mustache</code></pre>
<p>
We'd name our annotation file:
</p>
<pre><code>  00-elements/images/landscape-16x9.md
</code></pre>

<h4>Annotating Pseudo-Patterns</h4>
<p>
To annotate pseudo-patterns, replace the tilde sign (<code>~</code>) with a hyphen (<code>-</code>) when naming your annotation file.
</p>
<p>
For example, to document the following pseudo-pattern:
</p>
<pre><code>  00-elements/button/button~red.json
</code></pre>
<p>
We'd name our documentation file:
</p>
<pre><code>  00-elements/button/button-red.md
</code></pre>

<h4>Global Annotation File</h4>
<p>Example:</p>
<pre><code>  ---
  el: .hamburger-navigation
  title: Hamburger Navigation
  ---
  Ich bin ein Hamburger.
  ~*~
  ---
  el: .hero
  title: Hero Image
  ---
  Large image front, top, center.
  ~*~
  ---
  el: .sub
  title: Subs
  ---
  Image links to content below Hero.
  ~*~
  ---
  el: .hoagie
  title: Hoagies
  ---
  More sandwiches.
</code></pre>
<p>Located at <code>source/_annotations</code>, it must be named with the <code>.md</code> extenstion, or whatever is configured as the <code>frontMatterExtension</code>. It can consist of any number of annotations, each separated by <code>~*~</code>. The pattern-specific annotation files can consist of multiple annotations as well, delimited the same way.</p>
